Alignment is the presence of peace, freedom, joy, and trust…

It says that what you sow you shall reap.

What you plant, you will harvest.

In the past, I planted stress, fear, not-good-enough, and the need to prove myself.

No matter what result I produced, I was going to harvest that.

The seed of real estate was sown in me as a trainer back in 2014, as I was coaching and training my clients in who were in this industry.

However, I was so tied to the way I thought things needed to look, that I couldn’t see any other path. 

Till finally I started to learn the art of surrender.

There’s something exceedingly greater trying to work through us at all times.

The question is whether or not we are present enough to hear the still, small voice.

That’s how it works, you begin the process of surrendering, listen, and then walk through the doors as they open.

Then just show up with excitement and wonder and great things begin to happen!

I’m so grateful to be able to help my clients not only find a home to live in, but a place to build their legacy. 

Couldn’t do it without the amazing team I’m a part of!

I’d be honored to support you whether you’re purchasing your first home, or the 50th in your portfolio.

I failed to complete my first 50k ultra marathon...

But this experience was anything but a failure!

10 weeks ago, the furthest I had EVER run was 6 miles, and coming into race week, I didn’t even think I’d be able to participate because of intense (growing-pains-like) knee pain. 

2 weeks before the race, I had completed my longest training run of 20 miles, and after that developed the knee pain.

I decided to start the race slow and pace myself, and started feeling the knee pain again right about 4 miles.

At 6 miles I wanted to tap out cause of the pain…but I sucked up my pride and decided to use hiking poles from that point on.

Doing this helped me realized how I don’t receive well, and tend to do things my way (what I’ve always done).

In full tears, I caught my second wind and was feeling great, but the knee pain started to come back again…

Long story short, coming down 5500 feet of elevation is a beast on your knees, and I was able to run a couple hundred feet, and then walk till the pain went away (mostly).

But coming up on 6 miles left in the race, the pain was there constantly and I decided to tap out. 

As an athlete, I went into this wanting to test my fitness and see how I stacked up with people that had been doing this sport for years. 

And even though I wasn’t able to test that part of me, my true gain was that I was able to let go of needing to achieve and perform.

To run my race.

My fitness was on point, I trained well for this experience, and I will for sure be back for more!

There is no failure…

Only learning. 

And I signed up for this to learn more about myself, not to win a medal.

So I couldn’t be more grateful for this experience and I have a new appreciation of this sport! 

You must “fail” in order to grow, but the only true failure is not even stepping into the arena.

Till the next one…
